Note:
FREEBSD ARM64 (AArch64) THREADING - native thr_new syscall implementation

Implements the 32-proc threading API for FreeBSD running on ARM64 (AArch64)
using the direct thr_new / thr_exit / thr_self / thr_set_name / _umtx_op /
nanosleep / sched_yield / cpuset_getaffinity syscalls per the
FreeBSD sys/kern/syscalls.master numbering. No libthr, no libc — every
primitive bottoms out at `svc #0`.

Syscall numbers (FreeBSD sys/kern/syscalls.master — identical between
amd64 and arm64; only the ABI mechanism differs):
  SYS_thr_new              = 455   (kern_thr.c)
  SYS_thr_exit             = 431   (kern_thr.c)
  SYS_thr_self             = 432   (kern_thr.c)
  SYS_thr_set_name         = 464   (kern_thr.c)
  SYS__umtx_op             = 454   (kern_umtx.c)
  SYS_sched_yield          = 331   (kern_synch.c)
  SYS_nanosleep            = 240   (kern_time.c)
  SYS_cpuset_getaffinity   = 487   (kern_cpuset.c)
  SYS_mmap                 = 477   (vm_mmap.c, routed via syscall_mmap dispatcher)
  SYS_munmap               = 73    (vm_mmap.c, routed via syscall_munmap dispatcher)

References:
  sys/kern/kern_thr.c        — thr_new, thr_exit, thr_self implementations
  sys/sys/thr.h              — struct thr_param definition (96-byte layout)
  sys/kern/kern_umtx.c       — _umtx_op operations dispatch
  sys/sys/umtx.h             — UMTX_OP_* operation constants
  sys/kern/syscalls.master   — canonical syscall number assignments

The thread_create primitive constructs a struct thr_param in mmap-backed
memory, populates start_func/arg/stack/stack_size, and invokes thr_new
via inline assembly using the AAPCS64 / ARM64 svc #0 mechanics. Unlike
Linux clone(), FreeBSD's thr_new takes a pre-formed struct pointer —
the kernel jumps directly into start_func(arg) inside the new thread;
no trampoline shim is needed. On user-function return the thread invokes
thr_exit(NULL) to terminate cleanly. All locking primitives use _umtx_op
with UMTX_OP_WAIT_UINT_PRIVATE (op=15) and UMTX_OP_WAKE_PRIVATE (op=18)
— the FreeBSD analogue of Linux futex private operations.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/syscall.runa" as Syscall
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/atomic_core.runa" as Atomic

Note:
============================================================================
THREAD CREATION
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "thread_create" takes function_ptr as Integer, arg_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Create a new POSIX-style thread on FreeBSD/ARM64 using the SYS_thr_new
    (455) syscall directly. We bypass libthr/libc entirely so the Runa
    runatime has no external dependency for thread spawning.

    FreeBSD's thr_new differs fundamentally from Linux clone(): rather than
    taking flag/stack/tls arguments inline, it accepts a single pointer to
    a struct thr_param plus the struct size. The kernel reads start_func,
    arg, stack_base, stack_size from the struct and starts the new thread
    executing start_func(arg) directly — no userspace trampoline needed.

    The thr_param structure (sys/sys/thr.h) — 96 bytes on arm64:
      +0   start_func   (void (*)(void *))   — entry point
      +8   arg          (void *)              — argument passed to start_func
      +16  stack_base   (char *)              — lowest stack address
      +24  stack_size   (size_t)              — stack region size
      +32  tls_base     (char *)              — TLS region (NULL = none)
      +40  tls_size     (size_t)              — TLS region size
      +48  child_tid    (long *)              — kernel stores new TID here
      +56  parent_tid   (long *)              — kernel stores TID here (parent-visible)
      +64  flags        (int)                 — THR_* flags (0 = default)
      +68  (4 bytes padding for rtp alignment)
      +72  rtp          (struct rtprio *)     — realtime priority (NULL = inherit)
      +80  spare[3]     (int[3])              — reserved (zero)
      +92  (4 bytes trailing struct padding)

    On success: thr_new returns 0 in both parent and child. The new TID is
    written to child_tid (and parent_tid). On failure: returns -errno.

    Contract: returns child TID (positive) on success, -errno on failure.
    This matches the linux_arm64 sibling's return-value semantics so
    cross-platform thread code sees identical results.

    Stack: we mmap a 64 KiB anonymous region (PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE,
    MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_ANONYMOUS). The thr_param struct is placed in a
    separate mmap region of 128 bytes (96 needed, padded to 128 for
    alignment headroom and future-proofing against thr_param extensions).

    The struct, stack, and TID slot mappings remain live after thr_new
    returns — the kernel may still be reading them as the new thread
    initializes. They are leaked at the per-thread level; the Runa
    runatime's thread-join path is responsible for unmap on join. This
    matches the linux_arm64 sibling's lifecycle semantics.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Three-phase implementation:
      Phase 1 (Runa-level): mmap a 64 KiB stack; mmap an 8-byte TID slot
      (the kernel writes the child TID here); mmap a 128-byte thr_param
      region. Populate the struct fields via memory_set_int64 /
      memory_set_int32.

      Phase 2 (inline-asm): a single Inline Assembly block performs the
      thr_new syscall using AAPCS64 / ARM64 svc #0 mechanics:
        1. mov x8, #455           ; SYS_thr_new
        2. ldr x0, [fp, #-X]      ; X0 = thr_param pointer
        3. mov x1, #96            ; X1 = sizeof(struct thr_param)
        4. svc #0                 ; invoke thr_new
        5. str x0, [fp, #-Y]      ; raw return -> result_raw

      Phase 3 (Runa-level): if result_raw == 0, read the TID the kernel
      wrote into the tid_slot and return it. If result_raw < 0 (negative
      errno), return result_raw directly so callers can branch on
      sign. The parent path takes only the syscall round-trip; the
      child path is entered by the kernel directly at function_ptr —
      execution there is entirely outside this Process.

    Child cleanup contract: on return from function_ptr the child's
    saved-LR must point at a thr_exit call. Since the kernel jumps
    directly into function_ptr without a return address on the stack,
    callers MUST end their thread function with `proc thread_exit
    from Threading with 0` — otherwise the thread will execute random
    memory after function_ptr returns. This matches POSIX pthread
    behavior where pthread_exit is the documented exit path.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    - 64 KiB stack: larger than the linux_arm64 sibling (8 KiB) because
      FreeBSD's default libthr stack is 2 MiB and many existing FreeBSD
      libraries assume generous stack headroom. 64 KiB is a
      production-safe minimum that still keeps per-thread memory cost
      under 1 MiB total (stack + struct + TID slot).
    - Direct syscall avoids the ~200 ns libthr setup cost.
    - The thr_param construction is ~10 int64 stores + 1 mmap; the
      total parent-side cost is ~3 syscalls (2 mmap + 1 thr_new).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    - The new thread shares the parent's full address space, FDs, and
      signal handlers (FreeBSD thr_new always creates a same-process
      thread; there is no "share-nothing" mode like Linux clone).
      Sandboxed callers must apply Capsicum / jail filters in the parent
      BEFORE invoking thread_create.
    - The stack mmap is PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE only (no PROT_EXEC);
      W^X is enforced; the child cannot execute code from its own stack.
    - The thr_param mmap leaks one 128-byte region per thread create.
      Callers can recover it via the TID-slot mmap pointer if they
      track it — current API does not expose this for simplicity.
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Allocate 64 KiB stack for the new thread (mmap MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS, PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE).
    Let stack_size be 65536
    Let stack be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, stack_size, 3, 4098, -1, 0
    If stack is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If

    Note: Allocate 8-byte TID slot — the kernel writes the new thread's TID here via child_tid.
    Let tid_slot be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 8, 3, 4098, -1, 0
    If tid_slot is less than 0:
        proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with stack, stack_size
        Return -2
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tid_slot, 0, 0

    Note: Allocate 128 bytes for the thr_param struct (96 needed + headroom).
    Let param_ptr be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 128, 3, 4098, -1, 0
    If param_ptr is less than 0:
        proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with stack, stack_size
        proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with tid_slot, 8
        Return -3
    End If

    Note:
    Populate the thr_param struct per sys/sys/thr.h layout:
      +0   start_func     = function_ptr
      +8   arg            = arg_ptr
      +16  stack_base     = stack
      +24  stack_size     = stack_size
      +32  tls_base       = 0  (kernel allocates default TLS)
      +40  tls_size       = 0
      +48  child_tid      = tid_slot
      +56  parent_tid     = tid_slot   (same slot — kernel writes both)
      +64  flags          = 0
      +68  (4 bytes padding, leave zero)
      +72  rtp            = 0  (NULL = inherit parent priority)
      +80..+92  spare[3]  = 0
    :End Note
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with param_ptr, 0, function_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with param_ptr, 8, arg_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with param_ptr, 16, stack
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with param_ptr, 24, stack_size
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with param_ptr, 32, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with param_ptr, 40, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with param_ptr, 48, tid_slot
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with param_ptr, 56, tid_slot
    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with param_ptr, 64, 0
    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with param_ptr, 68, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with param_ptr, 72, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with param_ptr, 80, 0
    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with param_ptr, 88, 0
    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with param_ptr, 92, 0

    Let result_raw be 0

    Inline Assembly att:
        # FreeBSD ARM64 thr_new syscall. The "att" dialect qualifier tells
        # Runa's codegen to emit this block verbatim (no .intel_syntax
        # noprefix / .att_syntax prefix wrappers). The block contains pure
        # ARM64 mnemonics for the AArch64 GNU assembler to consume when
        # this file is targeted at an arm64 backend. On the current
        # x86_64-only codegen, this file is parsed and emitted but not
        # currently routed to an arm64 assembler — that handoff lands
        # when the arm64 backend comes online.
        #
        # AAPCS64 / FreeBSD ARM64 syscall ABI:
        #   X8 = syscall number (455 = SYS_thr_new)
        #   X0 = arg1 (struct thr_param *)
        #   X1 = arg2 (int param_size = sizeof(struct thr_param) = 96)
        # Returns 0 in both parent and child on success, -errno on failure.
        # Note: The child never returns from svc #0 in this frame — the
        # kernel jumps directly into start_func(arg) on a fresh stack.
        # Only the parent reaches the `str x0, [fp, #-X]` below.
        #
        # Local variable frame layout (allocation order = declaration order):
        #   function_ptr     -> fp - 8
        #   arg_ptr          -> fp - 16
        #   stack_size       -> fp - 24
        #   stack            -> fp - 32
        #   tid_slot         -> fp - 40
        #   param_ptr        -> fp - 48
        #   result_raw       -> fp - 56
        # result_raw at fp-56 receives the parent's syscall return value.

        mov x8, #455              # SYS_thr_new
        ldr x0, [fp, #-48]        # X0 = param_ptr
        mov x1, #96               # X1 = sizeof(struct thr_param)
        svc #0                    # invoke thr_new
        str x0, [fp, #-56]        # store raw return value
    End Assembly

    Note:
    Parse the result. FreeBSD's thr_new returns 0 (in both parent and child)
    on success; -errno on failure. The TID is in tid_slot (written by the
    kernel via child_tid pointer). If the syscall failed, return the negative
    errno directly.
    :End Note
    If result_raw is less than 0:
        Return result_raw
    End If

    Let tid be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with tid_slot, 0
    Return tid
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
THREAD LIFECYCLE
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "thread_join" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Block the calling thread until the target thread (identified by its TID
    handle) terminates. FreeBSD does not auto-clear a kernel-managed TID
    address on exit the way Linux does with CLONE_CHILD_CLEARTID; instead,
    we use _umtx_op UMTX_OP_WAIT_UINT_PRIVATE (op=15) on the TID value
    itself as the blocking primitive. The thread's death does not directly
    wake this wait — proper join requires the dying thread (in thread_exit)
    to issue a UMTX_OP_WAKE on the same address before invoking
    SYS_thr_exit. Since the kernel provides no automatic notification, the
    joining thread polls thr_kill2-style: it issues a bounded UMTX_OP_WAIT
    with a short timeout, then checks the TID slot. If the slot is zero
    (set by the exiting thread) we return success.

    For this implementation we use the simpler model of waiting on the
    handle (TID) itself with expected value = handle; the dying thread's
    convention is to zero the slot then UMTX_OP_WAKE. If a thread exits
    without cooperating, this join will block indefinitely — same
    contract as Linux futex-based join.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Issue _umtx_op(addr=handle, op=UMTX_OP_WAIT_UINT_PRIVATE (15),
    val=handle, uaddr=NULL, uaddr2=NULL) via the platform-routed syscall_5
    dispatcher with syscall number = SYS__umtx_op (454). The kernel returns
    0 when woken, or -EAGAIN if the value has already changed (thread
    already signaled exit). Either outcome is a successful join.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Pure kernel-blocking call; the thread is descheduled until the kernel
    wakes it on UMTX_OP_WAKE. No spin, no userspace polling.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The handle must be a TID owned by the same process as the caller —
    _umtx_op rejects addresses outside the caller's address space with
    -EFAULT.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let umtx_wait be 15
    Return proc syscall_5 from Syscall with 454, handle, umtx_wait, handle, 0, 0
End Process

Process called "thread_detach" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    On FreeBSD the kernel auto-reaps a thread once it exits (no explicit
    detach syscall is required — the kernel does not track join state
    separately from libthr-level bookkeeping). The function exists for
    ABI symmetry with platforms that DO require a detach call; on FreeBSD
    it is a true no-op.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Return 1 to signal "successfully detached" without invoking the kernel.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Zero-cost (one register load, one return).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No kernel transition; no permission considerations.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "thread_exit" takes exit_code as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Terminate the calling thread immediately. FreeBSD's SYS_thr_exit (431)
    is the per-thread exit syscall — distinct from SYS_exit (1) which
    terminates the whole process. The argument is a "state" pointer
    (long *) used for join notification: if non-NULL the kernel zeroes
    the pointed-to long on exit. We pass NULL because our thread_join
    model uses caller-side UMTX_OP_WAIT on the TID rather than kernel-
    managed exit notification.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Issue syscall_1(SYS_thr_exit=431, state=NULL=0). The exit_code
    parameter is accepted for API symmetry with Linux thread_exit but
    not propagated — FreeBSD thr_exit has no exit-status semantics
    (the kernel does not record per-thread exit values; whole-process
    exit status is set via SYS_exit only). The function never returns.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single syscall; this function never returns.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Affects only the calling thread; other threads in the process
    continue running.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_1 from Syscall with 431, 0
End Process

Process called "thread_current_id" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Return the kernel TID of the calling thread (distinct from PID in
    multi-threaded processes). FreeBSD provides SYS_thr_self (432) which
    writes the caller's TID to a user-supplied long * and returns 0/-errno.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. mmap an 8-byte slot for the TID output.
    2. Invoke syscall_1(SYS_thr_self=432, slot_ptr).
    3. Read the TID from the slot.
    4. munmap the slot.
    5. Return the TID.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mmap + one syscall + one munmap; the mmap pair adds ~150 ns
    overhead. Callers who query TID in hot paths should cache the
    result at thread-start time.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No permission requirements; TID is always observable by the thread
    itself. The slot mmap is process-private.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let slot be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 8, 3, 4098, -1, 0
    If slot is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with slot, 0, 0

    proc syscall_1 from Syscall with 432, slot

    Let tid be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slot, 0
    proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with slot, 8

    Return tid
End Process

Process called "thread_yield" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Voluntarily yield the CPU to the scheduler. Useful for cooperative
    spin-loops and busy-wait fallback paths. FreeBSD provides
    SYS_sched_yield (331) which returns 0 unconditionally on success.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Route through syscall_0(331). The kernel returns 0; we forward that.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Triggers a scheduler invocation; cheap if no contention, expensive
    (microseconds) under load. Prefer _umtx_op WAIT for real blocking.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Affects only the caller's scheduling state; no privileges required.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_0 from Syscall with 331
End Process

Process called "thread_sleep" takes microseconds as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Sleep the calling thread for the requested duration (microseconds).
    Implemented via nanosleep (SYS_nanosleep = 240 on FreeBSD); takes a
    timespec { tv_sec, tv_nsec } pointer. We convert microseconds to that
    split-form before issuing the syscall.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Decompose microseconds into seconds + remainder.
    2. Multiply remainder by 1000 to get nanoseconds.
    3. mmap a 16-byte region for the timespec struct (tv_sec at +0,
       tv_nsec at +8, both int64).
    4. Write the fields via memory_set_int64.
    5. Invoke syscall_2(240, timespec_ptr, NULL_remainder_ptr).
    6. Unmap the timespec region.
    7. Return the syscall result (0 on full sleep, -EINTR if interrupted).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    mmap+munmap overhead is ~2 syscalls beyond the nanosleep itself. For
    high-frequency micro-sleeps consider preallocating a per-thread
    timespec scratch buffer.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No special privileges; nanosleep is unrestricted. The mmap is
    PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE, MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS, so the timespec is
    not visible to other processes.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let seconds be microseconds divided by 1000000
    Let remaining_us be microseconds modulo by 1000000
    Let nanoseconds be remaining_us multiplied by 1000

    Note: Allocate timespec (16 bytes: tv_sec int64, tv_nsec int64).
    Let timespec_ptr be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 16, 3, 4098, -1, 0
    If timespec_ptr is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with timespec_ptr, 0, seconds
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with timespec_ptr, 8, nanoseconds

    Note: nanosleep(timespec_ptr, NULL remainder_ptr).
    Let result be proc syscall_2 from Syscall with 240, timespec_ptr, 0

    proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with timespec_ptr, 16

    Return result
End Process

Process called "thread_set_name" takes name as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Set a human-readable name for the calling thread (visible via
    procstat -t and in kernel debugger output). FreeBSD provides
    SYS_thr_set_name (464) which takes (lwpid_t tid, const char *name).
    Passing tid=-1 targets the current thread.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Route through syscall_2(464, -1, name_ptr). name_ptr must point to a
    null-terminated string of at most MAXCOMLEN (19) bytes plus terminator.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One-time setup cost (~100 ns); the name persists for the thread's
    lifetime. No effect on hot-path performance.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The caller can name any thread in the same process by TID; passing
    -1 (self) is unprivileged.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_2 from Syscall with 464, -1, name
End Process

Process called "thread_get_name" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    FreeBSD exposes thread names via procstat -t /proc/<pid>/status but
    has no read-side syscall paired with thr_set_name (the value is
    write-only at the syscall layer). To preserve the 32-proc dispatcher
    signature (returns Integer, no out-parameter), this implementation
    returns 0 as a sentinel meaning "not retrieved here". Callers who
    need the name should parse /proc/<pid>/status (procfs) or use
    libutil's kinfo_getproc + ki_tdname.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Return 0 unconditionally — the contract has no buffer slot to write
    into; promoting this to an out-param requires changing the dispatcher
    ABI across all 18 platforms, which is out of scope for this primitive.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Zero cost; no syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No kernel transition.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return 0
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
MUTEX (_umtx_op-backed)
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "mutex_create" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocate a 4-byte umtx word (initialized to 0 = unlocked) via mmap.
    The mutex handle is the umtx word's address. All mutex operations
    are pure userspace until contention is detected, at which point
    UMTX_OP_WAIT_UINT_PRIVATE / UMTX_OP_WAKE_PRIVATE descend into the
    kernel.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    mmap 4 bytes PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS; on
    failure return 0 (caller treats 0 as null-handle). Write 0 to the
    word to ensure deterministic unlocked state.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mmap call per mutex — coarse. Callers creating many mutexes
    should batch into an arena; this primitive optimizes for correctness
    over allocator throughput.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The mapping is process-private (MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_ANONYMOUS) — no
    cross-process leakage of the umtx word.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let umtx_word be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 4, 3, 4098, -1, 0
    If umtx_word is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with umtx_word, 0, 0
    Return umtx_word
End Process

Process called "mutex_destroy" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the 4-byte umtx-word mapping. Callers MUST ensure no other
    thread holds or is waiting on the mutex — destroying a held umtx
    is a use-after-free hazard.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    munmap(handle, 4) via the platform-routed dispatcher.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One munmap syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller must own the mapping (mmap-returned addresses are private).
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with handle, 4
End Process

Process called "mutex_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Acquire the mutex via a CAS-first / _umtx_op-WAIT-fallback protocol:
      1. Fast path: atomic CAS(handle, expected=0, desired=1). If the word
         was unlocked (0), we now hold it (1) and return immediately —
         no kernel transition.
      2. Slow path: word was nonzero (held by another thread). Spin-load
         the word; on each observation that it is 0 retry the CAS. If the
         word is still nonzero, issue _umtx_op(UMTX_OP_WAIT_UINT_PRIVATE
         = 15, val=1). The kernel parks the caller until mutex_unlock
         issues UMTX_OP_WAKE_PRIVATE.

    UMTX_OP_WAIT_UINT_PRIVATE / UMTX_OP_WAKE_PRIVATE are FreeBSD's
    process-private fast-path operations — analogous to Linux
    FUTEX_PRIVATE_FLAG. They skip vnode-based identification used by
    cross-process umtx and use a process-local hash table.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Two-phase loop matching the linux_arm64 sibling exactly. The atomic_*
    operations bottom out at ARM64 LDAXR/STLXR (release/acquire) inside
    atomic_core; the umtx syscall number is SYS__umtx_op = 454.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Uncontended acquire: ~3 instructions (1 CAS + 1 branch + 1 return).
    Contended path: 1 syscall per wakeup; the kernel batches wakes.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private umtx (UMTX_OP_*_PRIVATE) — no cross-process
    contention or signaling.
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Fast path
    Let expected be 0
    Let success be proc atomic_compare_and_swap from Atomic with handle, expected, 1
    If success is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Slow path: UMTX_OP_WAIT_UINT_PRIVATE = 15.
    Let umtx_wait be 15
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let current be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with handle, 0
        If current is equal to 0:
            Set success to proc atomic_compare_and_swap from Atomic with handle, 0, 1
            If success is equal to 1:
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
        proc syscall_5 from Syscall with 454, handle, umtx_wait, 1, 0, 0
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "mutex_unlock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the mutex (clear the umtx word to 0) and wake one waiter.
    The release barrier (memory_barrier_release) ensures all prior writes
    by the unlocking thread are visible to the next acquirer before the
    word goes to 0.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. memory_set_int32(handle, 0, 0) — release the word.
    2. memory_barrier_release — ARM64 DMB ISH inside atomic_core.
    3. syscall_5(454, handle, UMTX_OP_WAKE_PRIVATE = 18, 1, 0, 0)
       — wake exactly one waiter (val = 1).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Issues an unconditional _umtx_op wake syscall (FreeBSD sysnum 454,
    UMTX_OP_WAKE_PRIVATE) on every release; the kernel returns zero work
    when no thread is parked on the address. Per-call cost is dominated
    by the user-to-kernel transition (svc #0 plus FreeBSD's sysentvec
    dispatch), so the unconditional path keeps the release sequence
    branch-free on ARM64.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private umtx; no cross-process effect.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with handle, 0, 0
    proc memory_barrier_release from Atomic

    Let umtx_wake be 18
    proc syscall_5 from Syscall with 454, handle, umtx_wake, 1, 0, 0

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "mutex_try_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Non-blocking acquire: attempt the CAS once; return success/failure
    without spinning or syscalling. Used by lock-elision and try-acquire
    patterns.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single atomic_compare_and_swap(handle, 0, 1); return its result.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Constant-time, no syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Atomic-only; no kernel transition.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let expected be 0
    Let success be proc atomic_compare_and_swap from Atomic with handle, expected, 1
    Return success
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
SEMAPHORE (_umtx_op-backed counting semaphore)
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "semaphore_create" takes initial_count as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocate a 4-byte counter word initialized to initial_count. The word
    doubles as a umtx address for blocking waiters when the counter
    reaches 0.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    mmap 4 bytes (PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE, MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS); on
    failure return 0. Initialize the word to initial_count.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mmap per semaphore; consider arena-pooling for bulk usage.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private mapping.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let sem_word be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 4, 3, 4098, -1, 0
    If sem_word is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with sem_word, 0, initial_count
    Return sem_word
End Process

Process called "semaphore_destroy" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the counter mapping. Caller must ensure no thread is parked
    on the semaphore via UMTX_OP_WAIT_UINT_PRIVATE.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    munmap(handle, 4).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One munmap syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller owns the mapping.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with handle, 4
End Process

Process called "semaphore_wait" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Atomically decrement the counter; if the pre-decrement value was > 0
    the wait succeeded immediately. Otherwise restore the counter and
    park on the umtx via UMTX_OP_WAIT_UINT_PRIVATE.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Loop:
      1. Load current counter.
      2. If > 0: atomic_fetch_add(handle, -1); if pre-value > 0 we succeeded.
         If a race made pre-value <= 0, restore via atomic_fetch_add(+1).
      3. Else: _umtx_op(handle, UMTX_OP_WAIT_UINT_PRIVATE = 15, 0, 0, 0).
      4. Loop.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Uncontended: 2 atomics + 1 load. Contended: 1 syscall per wake.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private umtx.
    @End Security_Scope

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let current be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with handle, 0
        If current is greater than 0:
            Let new_val be current minus 1
            Let old_val be proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, -1
            If old_val is greater than 0:
                Return 1
            End If
            proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, 1
        End If

        proc syscall_5 from Syscall with 454, handle, 15, 0, 0, 0
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "semaphore_signal" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Increment the counter and wake one waiter. The increment is atomic
    so concurrent signals do not lose counts.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. atomic_fetch_add(handle, 1).
    2. syscall_5(454, handle, UMTX_OP_WAKE_PRIVATE = 18, 1, 0, 0).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Always wakes; no "has_waiters" gating (see mutex_unlock comment).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private umtx.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, 1

    Let umtx_wake be 18
    proc syscall_5 from Syscall with 454, handle, umtx_wake, 1, 0, 0

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "semaphore_try_wait" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Non-blocking variant of semaphore_wait: attempt the decrement once
    without descending into the kernel. Returns 1 on success, 0 if the
    counter is at 0 (would block).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Snapshot the counter; if > 0 attempt atomic_fetch_add(-1). On lost
    race (pre-value <= 0), restore via +1 and return 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Constant-time, no syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Atomic-only; no kernel transition.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let current be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with handle, 0
    If current is greater than 0:
        Let old_val be proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, -1
        If old_val is greater than 0:
            Return 1
        End If
        proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
CONDITION VARIABLE (sequence-numbered umtx)
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "condvar_create" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocate a 4-byte sequence word (initialized to 0). The word is
    bumped on every signal/broadcast; waiters check the pre-wait value
    via UMTX_OP_WAIT_UINT_PRIVATE-with-expected, which atomically blocks
    only if the sequence has not changed.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    mmap 4 bytes; init word to 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mmap per condvar; pool with arena for bulk use.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private mapping.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let cv_word be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 4, 3, 4098, -1, 0
    If cv_word is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with cv_word, 0, 0
    Return cv_word
End Process

Process called "condvar_destroy" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the sequence-word mapping.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    munmap(handle, 4).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One munmap.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller owns the mapping.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with handle, 4
End Process

Process called "condvar_wait" takes cv_handle as Integer, mutex_handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Atomically release the associated mutex and block on the condition
    variable's sequence. Re-acquire the mutex before returning. The
    "atomicity" of release+wait is achieved by the UMTX_OP_WAIT_UINT
    expected-value check: if a signal raced in between unlock and wait,
    the sequence will have advanced and _umtx_op returns EAGAIN
    immediately without sleeping.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Snapshot the sequence number from the cv word.
    2. mutex_unlock(mutex_handle).
    3. syscall_5(454, cv_handle, UMTX_OP_WAIT_UINT_PRIVATE (15),
       expected = seq, 0, 0).
    4. mutex_lock(mutex_handle) — reacquire on wakeup.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Worst case: 2 syscalls (unlock-wake + wait) + 1 atomic reacquire.
    Best case (spurious wake): 1 syscall + 1 reacquire.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Both umtxes are process-private. The mutex must be held by the
    caller on entry (verified by mutex_unlock semantics).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let seq be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with cv_handle, 0

    mutex_unlock(mutex_handle)

    proc syscall_5 from Syscall with 454, cv_handle, 15, seq, 0, 0

    mutex_lock(mutex_handle)

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "condvar_timed_wait" takes cv_handle as Integer, mutex_handle as Integer, timeout_us as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Bounded variant of condvar_wait. FreeBSD's _umtx_op accepts a
    `struct _umtx_time` pointer in uaddr2 for timed waits — its layout
    is { struct timespec _timeout; uint32_t _flags; uint32_t _clockid }
    = 24 bytes. With flags=0 the timeout is interpreted as relative
    (CLOCK_REALTIME default). The function returns -ETIMEDOUT on
    timeout expiry.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Snapshot sequence.
    2. mutex_unlock.
    3. Decompose timeout_us into sec + nsec; mmap a 24-byte _umtx_time;
       write timespec at +0/+8, flags=0 at +16, clockid=0 at +20.
    4. _umtx_op(cv_handle, UMTX_OP_WAIT_UINT_PRIVATE (15), seq,
       sizeof(_umtx_time)=24, umtx_time_ptr).
       Note: FreeBSD's _umtx_op convention for timed wait uses arg4 =
       sizeof(timespec/timeoutstruct) and arg5 = pointer-to-timeoutstruct.
       Passing 24 in arg4 selects the _umtx_time interpretation; passing
       16 would select the older bare-timespec form.
    5. munmap the _umtx_time.
    6. mutex_lock.

    If the mmap fails we skip the wait altogether (degraded but safe —
    caller treats this as immediate timeout). The mutex is still
    reacquired so the caller's invariant holds.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two extra syscalls (mmap + munmap) compared to condvar_wait. For
    tight loops with frequent timed waits consider preallocating a
    per-thread _umtx_time scratch buffer.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private umtx; _umtx_time mapping is MAP_PRIVATE.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let seq be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with cv_handle, 0

    mutex_unlock(mutex_handle)

    Let seconds be timeout_us divided by 1000000
    Let remaining_us be timeout_us modulo by 1000000
    Let nanoseconds be remaining_us multiplied by 1000

    Let umtx_time_ptr be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 24, 3, 4098, -1, 0
    If umtx_time_ptr is greater than or equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with umtx_time_ptr, 0, seconds
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with umtx_time_ptr, 8, nanoseconds
        proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with umtx_time_ptr, 16, 0
        proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with umtx_time_ptr, 20, 0

        Let result be proc syscall_5 from Syscall with 454, cv_handle, 15, seq, 24, umtx_time_ptr

        proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with umtx_time_ptr, 24
    End If

    mutex_lock(mutex_handle)

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "condvar_signal" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Wake exactly one waiter blocked on the condvar. The sequence is
    bumped first so any in-flight wait sees a stale expected value and
    returns -EAGAIN.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. atomic_fetch_add(handle, 1) — advance sequence.
    2. _umtx_op(handle, UMTX_OP_WAKE_PRIVATE (18), 1, 0, 0) — wake one.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Always issues the wake syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private umtx.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, 1

    Let umtx_wake be 18
    proc syscall_5 from Syscall with 454, handle, umtx_wake, 1, 0, 0

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "condvar_broadcast" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Wake all waiters blocked on the condvar (vs condvar_signal's single
    wake). Used when the predicate change affects all waiters
    simultaneously.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. atomic_fetch_add(handle, 1) — advance sequence.
    2. _umtx_op(handle, UMTX_OP_WAKE_PRIVATE (18),
       INT_MAX = 2147483647, 0, 0). INT_MAX in the val slot means "wake
       every parked waiter".
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single syscall regardless of waiter count.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private umtx; the kernel only wakes threads in the caller's
    process.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, 1

    Let umtx_wake be 18
    Let int_max be 2147483647
    proc syscall_5 from Syscall with 454, handle, umtx_wake, int_max, 0, 0

    Return 1
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
READ-WRITE LOCK (single 32-bit word, MSB=writer, low bits=reader count)
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "rwlock_create" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocate a 4-byte state word. Encoding:
      bit 31      = 1 if a writer holds the lock (value is negative as
                    signed int32)
      bits 0..30 = number of readers currently holding the lock
    Initialized to 0 (no readers, no writer).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    mmap 4 bytes; init to 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mmap per rwlock.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private mapping.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let rwlock_word be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 4, 3, 4098, -1, 0
    If rwlock_word is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with rwlock_word, 0, 0
    Return rwlock_word
End Process

Process called "rwlock_destroy" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the state-word mapping.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    munmap(handle, 4).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One munmap.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Caller owns the mapping.
    @End Security_Scope

    Return proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with handle, 4
End Process

Process called "rwlock_read_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Acquire a shared (reader) lock. Spin-and-wait protocol:
      1. Snapshot the state word.
      2. If negative (writer holds it): UMTX_OP_WAIT_UINT_PRIVATE until
         state changes.
      3. Otherwise: attempt CAS(state, state+1). If lost race, retry.
    Multiple readers may hold the lock simultaneously (count increments).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Standard ticket-less reader entry loop. The UMTX_OP_WAIT uses the
    full state word as expected — if any change (writer release, new
    reader) occurs, the wait returns and we retry.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Uncontended: 1 load + 1 CAS = ~5 ns.
    Writer-blocked: kernel block via UMTX_OP_WAIT_UINT_PRIVATE.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private umtx.
    @End Security_Scope

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let current be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with handle, 0
        If current is less than 0:
            proc syscall_5 from Syscall with 454, handle, 15, current, 0, 0
        Otherwise:
            Let new_val be current plus 1
            Let old_val be proc atomic_compare_and_swap from Atomic with handle, current, new_val
            If old_val is equal to 1:
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "rwlock_write_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Acquire an exclusive (writer) lock. Writers wait for the state word
    to reach 0 (no readers, no writer), then CAS it to MIN_INT32
    (0x80000000) to claim sole ownership.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Spin loop:
      1. Snapshot state.
      2. If 0: attempt CAS(state, 0, MIN_INT32). On success: hold the lock.
      3. Otherwise: UMTX_OP_WAIT_UINT_PRIVATE(state).
    MIN_INT32 (-2147483648, hex 0x80000000) is chosen so the state word's
    sign bit (bit 31) is set when a writer holds it; reader code tests
    for "current < 0" to detect writer presence.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Uncontended write-lock acquire: 1 load + 1 CAS.
    Contended: O(N) syscalls in worst case (each reader/writer release
    wakes the writer for re-evaluation).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private umtx.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let write_bit be -2147483648

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let current be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with handle, 0
        If current is equal to 0:
            Let success be proc atomic_compare_and_swap from Atomic with handle, 0, write_bit
            If success is equal to 1:
                Return 1
            End If
        End If
        proc syscall_5 from Syscall with 454, handle, 15, current, 0, 0
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "rwlock_unlock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release whichever lock mode is held. If the state word is negative
    (writer held), clear it to 0 — the writer's exit unblocks the entire
    population. Otherwise (reader held), atomically decrement the reader
    count. Always wake all waiters so any blocked writer can re-evaluate.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Snapshot current state.
    2. If < 0: write 0 (clear writer flag).
       Else: atomic_fetch_add(handle, -1) — decrement reader count.
    3. memory_barrier_release.
    4. UMTX_OP_WAKE_PRIVATE(handle, INT_MAX) — wake everyone.

    The "wake all" choice (vs wake-one) is correct because a single
    writer-release may unblock multiple readers; a single reader-release
    may unblock a writer.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Always issues a wake syscall. Optimization opportunity: track waiter
    count to skip wake when no one is parked (deferred).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Process-private umtx.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let current be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with handle, 0
    If current is less than 0:
        proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with handle, 0, 0
    Otherwise:
        proc atomic_fetch_add from Atomic with handle, -1
    End If

    proc memory_barrier_release from Atomic

    Let umtx_wake be 18
    Let int_max be 2147483647
    proc syscall_5 from Syscall with 454, handle, umtx_wake, int_max, 0, 0

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "rwlock_try_read_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Non-blocking reader acquisition: snapshot the state; if a writer
    holds it (state < 0) fail immediately; otherwise attempt the
    single-shot CAS increment.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Snapshot + branch + CAS; no syscall.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Constant-time.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Atomic-only.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let current be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with handle, 0
    If current is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let new_val be current plus 1
    Let success be proc atomic_compare_and_swap from Atomic with handle, current, new_val
    Return success
End Process

Process called "rwlock_try_write_lock" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Non-blocking writer acquisition: single CAS from 0 to MIN_INT32.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    One CAS; return its result.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Constant-time.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Atomic-only.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let write_bit be -2147483648
    Let success be proc atomic_compare_and_swap from Atomic with handle, 0, write_bit
    Return success
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
Hardware Query - CPU Affinity-Based Concurrency Detection
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "hardware_concurrency" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Return the number of CPU cores available to the calling process.
    Uses cpuset_getaffinity(level=CPU_LEVEL_WHICH=2, which=CPU_WHICH_TID=1,
    id=-1 (self), setsize=128, mask) — fills a 1024-bit affinity mask,
    one bit per logical CPU the process may run on. We popcount the mask
    byte-by-byte via Kernighan's bit-clear trick.

    On any syscall failure we return 1 (never 0; callers expect a
    positive worker count and would divide-by-zero or spawn no threads
    otherwise).

    The cpuset_getaffinity ABI on FreeBSD:
      int cpuset_getaffinity(cpulevel_t level, cpuwhich_t which,
                             id_t id, size_t setsize, cpuset_t *mask);
    Level CPU_LEVEL_WHICH (2) + which CPU_WHICH_TID (1) + id -1 means
    "affinity of the current thread". Returns 0 on success (mask
    written), -errno on failure.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. mmap 128 bytes for the mask (PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE,
       MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS).
    2. Zero the buffer (defensive — the kernel only writes the bytes
       it uses, so uninitialized trailing bytes would inflate the
       popcount).
    3. syscall_5(SYS_cpuset_getaffinity = 487, level=2, which=1,
       id=-1, setsize=128, mask_ptr). Returns 0 on success, -errno on
       failure. Unlike Linux's sched_getaffinity (which returns the
       number of bytes written), FreeBSD's cpuset_getaffinity returns
       only 0/-errno — we always popcount all 128 bytes after success.
    4. Popcount the buffer: for each byte b, while b != 0,
       b = b & (b - 1); total_set += 1.
    5. munmap the buffer.
    6. Return max(total_set, 1).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mmap + one syscall + one munmap; popcount loop is O(128 * 8) =
    1024 iterations worst case. Result is typically cached by the
    runatime, so the cost is amortized across the process lifetime.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    cpuset_getaffinity is unrestricted for id=-1 (self thread). The
    mmap is process-private. No information leaks across processes.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let mask_buf be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, 128, 3, 4098, -1, 0
    If mask_buf is less than 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Zero the buffer
    Let zero_idx be 0
    While zero_idx is less than 128:
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with mask_buf, zero_idx, 0
        Set zero_idx to zero_idx plus 1
    End While

    Note: cpuset_getaffinity(CPU_LEVEL_WHICH=2, CPU_WHICH_TID=1, -1, 128, mask_buf).
    Let rc be proc syscall_5 from Syscall with 487, 2, 1, -1, 128, mask_buf
    If rc is less than 0:
        proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with mask_buf, 128
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Popcount over all 128 bytes (FreeBSD writes the entire mask region).
    Let total_set be 0
    Let byte_idx be 0
    While byte_idx is less than 128:
        Let byte_val be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with mask_buf, byte_idx
        While byte_val is not equal to 0:
            Let lowered be byte_val minus 1
            Set byte_val to byte_val bitwise and lowered
            Set total_set to total_set plus 1
        End While
        Set byte_idx to byte_idx plus 1
    End While

    proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with mask_buf, 128

    If total_set is less than 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return total_set
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Thread Scheduling Priority and Affinity
Note: ============================================================================
Note:
Stubs for this platform. Implementing these requires the platform-specific
priority/affinity syscall surface (pthread_setschedparam on POSIX,
SetThreadPriority on Windows, etc.). The Linux x86_64 / ARM64 / ARM32
implementations exercise the real syscalls; other platforms surface a
deterministic failure to the caller (the higher-level thread_core API
already routes failure correctly to its return-1/return-0 contracts).
:End Note

Process called "thread_set_priority" takes handle as Integer, priority as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Unimplemented on this platform; surface failure to the caller.
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "thread_get_priority" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Unimplemented on this platform; return the -999 sentinel
    Note: expected by thread_core::thread_get_priority.
    Return 0 minus 999
End Process

Process called "thread_set_affinity" takes handle as Integer, cpu_mask as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Unimplemented on this platform; surface failure to the caller.
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "thread_get_affinity" takes handle as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Unimplemented on this platform; return 0 mask (no CPUs known).
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "get_cpu_id" returns Integer:
    Note: Unimplemented on this platform; return -1 sentinel.
    Return 0 minus 1
End Process
